{"total":11990,"quota_max":10000,"quota_remaining":9803,"has_more":true,"items":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/69d6c826a7f23b9b80e624e30c2c7290?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15307/emilyj","reputation":14,"display_name":"emilyj"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":1,"post_id":31313,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428940618,"comment_id":52355,"body":"If you added DNA with a protonated phosphate backbone to a sample of pure water with pH of exactly 7.0, the extra protons on the backbone would be picked up by waters to create a deprotonated backbone and hydronium ion. The charge is still balanced, the backbone becomes negative and the hydronium is positive. The pH would change, becoming more acidic, I don&#39;t know how acidic, depends on the amount of DNA and equilibrium constants, and I don&#39;t want to do that math right now."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":31313,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428943961,"comment_id":52356,"body":"I&#39;d suggest specifying in your question that your system is just water at some sort of default conditions."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"c