. Bottom line it is not a simple pairwise comparison between two organisms coding sequences and I am not too surprise you see an organism being closer than you would expect. My advice to you is trust the phylogenetic tree."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd92d78ae4b6aa7c5001759824752737?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15330,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15330/ant","reputation":174,"display_name":"Ant"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429050351,"creation_date":1429050351,"body":"<blockquote>\n  <p>1.Is such an approach trying to quantify homology? Which i know is not correct as homology is qualitive measure.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>A common approach to identify orthologs (homology between two genes resulting from a speciation event) it 'best bidirectional match': if you blast gene A (in species 1) against all genes of species 2 the best match is gene B, <strong>and<\/strong> if you blast gene B against all genes of species 1 the best match is gene A.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>2.Can we compare the ratio of homology between the above 2 couples od species or such a comparison is biased?<\/p>\n  \n  <p>3.Shouldn't the ratio of homology be proportional to the evolutionary distance of the organisms (according to conservation)?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Not necessarly. The fact that two genes diverged a very long time ago does not prevent them from being homologous. Homology is about shared ancestry (here of two genes) and not about evolutionary distance.<\/p>\n\n<p>Could you clarify how you get the homologies? Did you compute them yourself (if so how) or did you use a specific database?<\/p>\n","answer_id":31353,"question_id":30759,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30759/homology-ratio-comparison-between-different-species","last_activity_date":1429050351,"creation_date":1427290607,"answer_count":1,"title":"Homology ratio comparison between different species","body":"<p>I found the following homology ratio:<\/p>\n\n<p>protein coding genes of the organism with an homolog in mouse / all protein coding genes in the organism<\/p>\n\n<p>I have done this for all protein coding genes between several organisms and mouse using a phylogenetic-based approach. I have noticed that the ratio found between an organism and mouse is greater than the ratio between another organism and mouse! On the other hand the second is evolutionary closer to mouse than the first.So:<\/p>\n\n<p>1.Is such an approach trying to quantify homology? Which i know is not correct as homology is qualitive measure.<\/p>\n\n<p>2.Can we compare the ratio of homology between the above 2 couples od species or such a comparison is biased?<\/p>\n\n<p>3.Shouldn't the ratio of homology be proportional to the evolutionary distance of the organisms (according to conservation)?<\/p>\n\n<p>As you can understand, in the way i calculate the above ratio, i don't take into account the one-to-many or many-to many relationships! I just take into account the genes that have at least one homolog in mouse..is that the bias of my calculation?<\/p>\n","question_id":30759,"tags":["evolution","homology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":56,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/edd4f46b96f5194781ddbe75527f8e23?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15338,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15338/andrey","reputation":133,"display_name":"Andrey"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429048173,"creation_date":1429048173,"body":"