ain, Szentagothai estimated\n  that <strong>each neuron is able to contact any other neuron with no more than\n  six interneuronal connections\u2014\u201csix degrees of separation.\u201d<\/strong><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://www.nature.com/polopoly_fs/7.2933.1329907514!/image/far-to-go.jpg_gen/derivatives/fullsize/far-to-go.jpg\" alt=\"\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Image Source: <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/polopoly_fs/7.2933.1329907514!/image/far-to-go.jpg_gen/derivatives/fullsize/far-to-go.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.nature.com/polopoly_fs/7.2933.1329907514!/image/far-to-go.jpg_gen/derivatives/fullsize/far-to-go.jpg<\/a><\/p>\n\n<h2>Why Brain beats Supercomputer?<\/h2>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Why is it so hard for computers to reproduce what your grey matter\n  does as a matter of course? <strong>Volume<\/strong>. The human brain consists of about\n  200 billion nerve cells (neurons) that are linked together by\n  trillions of connections called synapses. As the tiny electrical\n  impulses shoot across each neuron, they have to travel through these\n  synapses, each of which contains about 1000 different switches that\n  route that electrical impulse. In total, one <strong>human brain could contain\n  hundreds of trillions of these neural pathways<\/strong>. It's like a Choose\n  Your Own Adventure book that stretches from here to Jupiter.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":19768,"question_id":19767,"up_vote_count":19,"last_edit_date":1428883748},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":9,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aab80aeaf4754dee5d4a758db50e7213?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":460,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/460/memming","reputation":2145,"display_name":"Memming","accept_rate":70},"score":1,"post_id":31304,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428930955,"comment_id":52352,"body":"In my opinion this is a much better answer than Devashish Das (OP)&#39;s answer which got 15 up votes and is chosen as an answer at the moment."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/5Uayv.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":8186,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/8186/devashish-das","reputation":3783,"display_name":"Devashish Das","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":31304,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428987295,"comment_id":52397,"body":"Yes, I like this one too."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e32946c257cb4802dea738db1ecbf0c6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13345,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13345/theblackcat","reputation":121,"display_name":"TheBlackCat"},"score":0,"post_id":31304,"edited":false,"creation_date":1429044763,"comment_id":52438,"body":"It is kind of meaningless to compare an analog device with a digital one to begin with."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1429037412,"creation_date":1428897444,"body":"<p>There's a very big difference between doing the calculations needed to simulate the human brain (or any animal brain FTM - we can do a fairly decent job on C. elegans.), and doing computations.  While a basic leaky integrate &amp; fire model is fairly simple, to ACCURATELY simulate a single neuron in real time takes a pretty fast computer.  See e.g. these links for more <a href=\"http://www.neuron.yale.edu/neuron/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.neuron.yale.edu/neuron/<\/a>  <a href=\"http://bluebrain.epfl.ch/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://bluebrain.epfl.ch/<\/a>  <a href=\"http://www.artificialbrains.com/darpa-synapse-program\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.artificialbrains.com/darpa-synapse-program<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Thing is, brains do well what computers do poorly, and vice versa.  The HP12C calculator on my desk, made in the early '80s, can do many sorts of mathmatical calculations faster than I can, because brains aren't really optimized for doing e.g. compound interest calculations.  But my brain, or FTM my dog's brain, can do all the 'calculations' needed to process a stream of images, recognize that they show a ball, predict its path, and catch it - while simultaneously processing visual, auditory, olfactory, and kinesthetic inputs for obstacle avoidance and threat recognition. and (in my case, anyway) perhaps thinking about how to solve complex programming problems.<\/p>\n\n<p>PS: Maybe I should add that there are basically three different things that a computer can do in this context:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>1) Complex calculations, whether compound interest, weather modelling, seismic tomography or whatever.\n\n2) Simulating the actual behavior of a brain, or some subset of one, starting from a single neuron.  \n\n3) Trying to replicate what a brain does through algorithms, or Artificial Intelligence.\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<h1>1 is what we mostly use computers for, and they're way better at it than human brains.  #2 is a special case of #1, which we do because we don't have much of an idea how to do #3, and having a simulated brain we can alter at will might help in learning how real brains do what they do.<\/h1>\n","answer_id":31304,"question_id":19767,"up_vote_count":10,"last_edit_date":1429037412},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user11667"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429014211,"creation_date":1429014211,"body":"<p>A simple calculator (which is a computer) calculates 298465+46547 much faster than us. a PC forecast possible events faster than us. But even the fastest computer can't recognize a new pattern faster than us (the computer may never do that). So each one has its relative advantages.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31333,"question_id":19767,"up_vote_count":3}],"