 restriction enzymes are palindromic, so if you always read the sequence of each strand from 5&#39; to 3&#39; prime it will always be the same sequence. If, reading from 5&#39; to 3&#39; you specified the sequence CCTAGG then after PCR there would be absolutely no overhanging sticky ends on that end of the fragment. It would be completely blunt. BamHI cannot recognize or cut CCTAGG."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31199/closing-a-plasmid-by-ligation","last_activity_date":1429025765,"creation_date":1428595962,"answer_count":0,"title":"Closing a Plasmid by Ligation","body":"<p>I have been having trouble with what should be a fairly simple ligation. I had a plasmid that I needed to cut part out of, so I designed a couple PCR primers to do that. The plasmid already had a BamHI site on 1 side of the region I wanted to remove, so I made the other PCR primer with a BamHI site on its 5' end with 3 extra Cs so the restriction enzyme would bind better. Here is a crude diagram of what I tried to do:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/ChPPj.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>So I did the PCR and BamHI digest, it looked good on gel, so I purified it from the gel, got the concentration on the Nanodrop, and set up a ligation. <\/p>\n\n<p>However, I keep getting zero colonies. I have tried a 24 hour reaction at 4 degrees, and 10 minute reaction at room temp. I am currently trying a reaction where I supplement the buffer with fresh ATP, because the buffers are a little old. If that works, problem solved, if not, I am asking how to troubleshoot this.<\/p>\n\n<p>This seems like it should be relatively simple, because I have no insert, just trying to close an empty vector, which seems to happen on its own when I don't want it to and dephosphorylate the vector.<\/p>\n\n<p>UPDATE:<\/p>\n\n<p>The reaction with extra ATP did not produce colonies. I will keep trying. One idea I had was to do the PCR and then try blunt end ligation, since the Pfu polymerase should make blunt ends. Also got a new sample of ligase.<\/p>\n","question_id":31199,"tags":["pcr","cloning","ligation"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":72,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1429025765},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5cff3e84bcedd40163c74d33b827ac7c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/307/lancelafontaine","reputation":3814,"display_name":"LanceLafontaine","accept_rate":47},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/cc66cc37d65d76c2149e2b2b54b530d4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3336,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3336/ryan","reputation":1103,"display_name":"Ryan"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1386353526,"creation_date":1386024183,"body":"<p>I don't think repetitive sequences are intrinsically problematic to an <em>E coli<\/em>. Bacteria also deal with things like <a href=\"http://www.nature.com/embor/journal/v4/n2/full/embor733.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">polyadenylation<\/a>. Basically, you have nothing to lose from trying -- <em>E coli<\/em> is one of the more robust expression platforms, and it's difficult to predict whether the sequence will fold into some tertiary structure (which can easily impede translation.)<\/p>\n\n<p>So I think the predictability should be set at the baseline for <em>E coli<\/em> RNA polymerase error rate, which is about $10^{-5}$.<\/p>\n","answer_id":13764,"question_id":13618,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1386353526},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bd92d78ae4b6aa7c5001759824752737?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15330,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15330/ant","reputation":174,"display_name":"Ant"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur