fe, reproductive stem cells must age too. However one half of the DNA of some random old reproductive stem cell is eventually transferred through reproduction, and the ageing cycle begins again, with new somatic cells with long telomeres.<\/p>\n\n<p>What mechanisms can explain reproductive stem cells DNA do not age as somatic cells' DNA ? Or do we know how telomeres are growing back from old reproductive stem cells to gamete during meiosis ? Put another way, how is it possible that we are born with long telomeres ?<\/p>\n\n<p>I am sorry for the formulation of my question. I think it is understandable but not really well written. However I don't know how to formulate it another way yet. Do not hesitate to reformulate it if you feel like it.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks.<\/p>\n","question_id":31335,"tags":["stem-cells","reproductive-biology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":40,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZBeuU.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9020,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9020/look-behind-you","reputation":808,"display_name":"Look behind you","accept_rate":100},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/vnYni.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1916,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1916/mysky","reputation":1053,"display_name":"MySky","accept_rate":76},"score":0,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1429013284,"creation_date":1429013284,"body":"<p>This is the short answer from <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank%E2%80%93Starling_law#Physiology\" rel=\"nofollow\">wikipedia<\/a> :) :<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>As the heart fills with more blood than usual, the force of cardiac\n  muscular contractions increases.[2] This is a result of an increase in\n  the load experienced by each muscle fiber due to the extra blood load\n  entering the heart. The stretching of the muscle fibers augments\n  cardiac muscle contraction by increasing the calcium sensitivity of\n  the myofibrils, [3] causing a greater number of actin-myosin\n  cross-bridges to form within the muscle fibers. The force that any\n  single cardiac muscle fiber generates is proportional to the initial\n  sarcomere length (known as preload), and the stretch on the individual\n  fibers is related to the end-diastolic volume of the left and right\n  ventricles.<\/p>\n  \n  <p>In the human heart, maximal force is generated with an initial\n  sarcomere length of 2.2 micrometers, a length which is rarely exceeded\n  in the normal heart. Initial lengths larger or smaller than this\n  optimal value will decrease the force the muscle can achieve. For\n  larger sarcomere lengths, this is the result of less overlap of the\n  thin and thick filaments; for smaller sarcomere lengths, the cause is\n  the decreased sensitivity for calcium by the myofilaments.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>in one sentence, it is a response to tension.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31331,"question_id":31327,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31327/what-is-the-insight-of-frank-starling-law-of-the-heart","last_activity_date":1429013284,"creation_date":1428992539,"answer_count":1,"title":"What is the insight of Frank Starling law of the heart?","body":"<p>The Frank Starling law appears to be a trivial observation:<\/p>\n\n<p>stroke volume is directly related to the end diastolic volume<\/p>\n\n<p>In everyday language, as more blood fills the heart, the heart pumps more blood out.<\/p>\n\n<p>Can someone point out whether there are some inaccuracies in the above description because I don't understand why every article on FS law requires upward 20 pages. Even youtube video on this topic is 8 minutes long. <\/p>\n\n<p>What is the big idea here that I am missing?<\/p>\n","question_id":31327,"tags":["cardiology"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":31331,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":75,"up_vote_co