>\n\n<p>A badly resolved tree should show up in sets of randomly generated trees far more often than well resolved ones. <\/p>\n\n<p>See <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.2041-210X.2012.00196.x/abstract\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.2041-210X.2012.00196.x/abstract<\/a> <\/p>\n","answer_id":31276,"question_id":31274,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1428835716}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31274/what-does-saying-a-phylogenetic-tree-is-well-resolved-mean","last_activity_date":1428835716,"creation_date":1428834895,"answer_count":1,"title":"What does saying a phylogenetic tree is 'well resolved' mean?","body":"<p>I'm not sure what 'resolution' means in the context of phylogenies.<\/p>\n","question_id":31274,"tags":["bioinformatics","phylogenetics"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":true,"view_count":237,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/07eba579c3467c6d067db56a542046ff?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":15292,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15292/user15292","reputation":4,"display_name":"user15292"},"closed_date":1428828894,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":31235,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428710996,"comment_id":52227,"body":"this seems to be an opinion-based question. Also, it would be better to post your research as well as question. What sites are you talking about? Any papers? what is particular side of such survival are you interested in?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uTYSx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14826,"link":"http://biology.stackexchan