,"user_type":"registered","user_id":13212,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13212/user3059024","reputation":108,"display_name":"user3059024"},"score":0,"post_id":31236,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428750091,"comment_id":52245,"body":"Hi Andrev, this is great, thank you... By slope do you mean the derivative at the point where the function is evaluated or the slope of the straight line bit in the middle? If you mean the latter, then I can work this out from the graph I&#39;m looking at (since my data is from a paper). Essentially I&#39;m trying to build a mathematical model that incorporates this data, so the values of the top and bottom asymptote will be relative - meaning I have to just make them up and see if they fit."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d7c5cbd0c2f965a3712ff687c53f997?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14552,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14552/aaaaaa","reputation":2058,"display_name":"aaaaaa"},"score":0,"post_id":31236,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428777300,"comment_id":52257,"body":"i&#39;d say, &#39;slope of tangent to mid-point, e.g. EC50&#39;. And yes, that might be a way to go. After that you can stretch and shift curve so it goes not from 0 to 1, but, let&#39;s say, from 0.1 to 0.9."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428714247,"creation_date":1428710892,"body":"<p>Basic sigmoidal curve looks like that: zero at $-\\inf$ and one at $+\\inf$. All in between should look like an integral of gaussian distribution. Take a look on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution\" rel=\"nofollow\">this wiki page<\/a> for more information. Now, the question, why sigmoidal curve is integral of gaussian function, I will leave out for now. My understanding is that gaussian distribution tells you how much system response will increase (say, efficiency of treatment) if you increase stimulus by $dx$. E.g., how much response changes when you go from $5$ to $5+dx$ versus from $10$ to $10+dt$.<\/p>\n\n<p>The problem, as you might realize, that gaussian distribution has two parameters: mean value and width of the function. When you construct your fit, frist one will be 19nM, but second, $\\sigma$, is unknown from your question. What you don't know is how rapidly response changes when you increase concentration by little around your EC50. So all your sigmoidal plots will go through same point but with different slope, like that:<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/PKL9P.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Without knowing second parameter, $\\sigma$, it makes little sense to plot your sigmoidal curve. However, if you want to, this is MATLAB code. See that <em>cumsum()<\/em> function effectively integrates gaussian distribution rendering sigmoidal curve.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>c = 0:100; % range of concentrations you test\nsigma = 1; % unknown parameter\nm = 19; % your EC50 19 nM\ng = 1/(sigma*sqrt(2*pi))*exp(-((c - m).^2)/(2*sigma^2)); % gaussian\ngs = cumsum(g);\nplot(c, gs)\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you want, you can plot it with log-scale of X, using semilogx() instead of plot().<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>NB<\/strong> here I started with Gaussian function and its integral just as a wild guess. You real function <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigmoid_function\" rel=\"nofollow\">might very well be<\/a> something like $f(x)=\\frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}$. \"Sigmoid\" function is just description of general shape, not mathematical definition.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31236,"question_id":31234,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1428714247}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31234/given-an-ec50-value-how-do-i-reproduce-the-sigmoidal-curve-from-which-this-was","last_activity_date":1428725398,"creation_date":1428706634,"answer_count":1,"title":"Given an EC50 value, how do I reproduce the sigmoidal curve from which this was calculated?","body":"<p>All-trans retinoic acid (atRA) is a potent ligand for a nuclear receptor called retinoic acid receptor alpha (RARa). The concentration of atRA at which RARa is half maximal is 19nM. The dose-response curve is sigmoidal, with concentration (log scale) on the x-axis and percentage of maximal activity on the y.<\/p>\n\n<p>How would I use this information to reproduce the dose-response curve? <\/p>\n\n<p>Thanks<\/p>\n","question_id":31234,"tags":["biochemistry","physiology","pharmacology","pharmacokinetics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":31236,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":122,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1428725398},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/1368200828/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":14887,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14887/emilie-cuillery","reputation":16,"display_name":"Emilie Cuillery"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9bd7c0a93e1587d390866d374842b91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9829,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9829/luigi","reputation":2475,"display_name":"Luigi"},"score":1,"post_id":30347,"edited":false,"creation_date":1426097614,"comment_id":50051,"body":"Inserting into the genome of what organism?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b10de963b115fd0720d6a558fd1ac06c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":10456,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/10456/march-ho","reputation":5867,"display_name":"March Ho","accept_rate":80},"score":0,"post_id":30347,"edited":false,"creation_date":1426100458,"comment_id":50056,"body":"Why not just make sure your inserted DNA segment contains the same CRISPR/Cas recognition site, so you can just cut it again?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputati