thrm{u_x(0,t)+\\frac{h(t)}{k(t)}u(0,t)=0}$$<\/p>\n\n<p>where $\\mathrm{k(t)}$ thermal conductivity and $\\mathrm{h(t)}$ heat tranfer coefficient.<\/p>\n\n<p>My Question: Is it possible that the ratio $\\mathrm{h(t)/k(t)}$ to be constant? Could anyone please help me? I have really no idea. <\/p>\n","question_id":31211,"tags":["biochemistry","mathematical-models","heat"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":1,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":49,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9121eae6ec065d957a1039e72d7e60bc?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":139,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/139/dragana-bozic","reputation":309,"display_name":"Dragana Bozic"},"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user132"},"score":0,"post_id":101,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323964439,"comment_id":84,"body":"The <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/tagged/gelred\">gelred<\/a> tag seemed a bit too specific..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/66c66c4d97a7bc3859a85253f003e1fb?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"moderator","user_id":6,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6/mad-scientist","reputation":6781,"display_name":"Mad Scientist","accept_rate":55},"score":6,"post_id":101,"edited":false,"creation_date":1323971936,"comment_id":105,"body":"Are you sure it&#39;s the staining, and not the gels themselves that are the problem?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1379a548b0ecfcbe5fe13f3bf1984a2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":51,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/51/mac-cowell","reputation":692,"display_name":"Mac Cowell"},"score":0,"post_id":101,"edited":false,"creation_date":1324006217,"comment_id":153,"body":"What wavelength and filter set are you using for visualizing your gels?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1379a548b0ecfcbe5fe13f3bf1984a2b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":51,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/51/mac-cowell","reputation":692,"display_name":"Mac Cowell"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":145,"edited":false,"creation_date":1380898897,"comment_id":14208,"body":"i&#39;ve also had the best resolution with pre-stained gels.  Even so, its better to take long time exposures of the gels on UV sometimes.  Hi Mac!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1324006675,"creation_date":1324006675,"body":"<p>I have had success with 1.5% agarose gels in TBE pre-stained with gelred.  I use a 10,000x stock solution of gelred sold by <a href=\"http://biotium.com\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://biotium.com<\/a>.  I visualize the gel on an old fotodyne UV transilluminator.<\/p>\n\n<p>After melting agarose in the appropriate volume of TBE in a microwave, I let it cool to about 50 C (I can touch the flask with the back of my hand without snatching it away) and then add the appropriate volume of stock gelred.  <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>For a 30 mL 1.5% agarose gel:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>mix 0.45g agarose + 30 mL 1x TBE<\/li>\n<li>microwave until agarose solution boils and clarifies<\/li>\n<li>let cool to around 50 C<\/li>\n<li>add 3 uL gelred<\/li>\n<li>swirl the mixture<\/li>\n<li>cast the gel (don't forget comb)<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>This typically works for me.  I run the gel in a 1x TBE buffer at around 120 volts.<\/p>\n","answer_id":145,"question_id":101,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3d9515a7c0965977892f1c897bf9191d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":96,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/96/bobtheowl2","reputation":390,"display_name":"bobtheowl2","accept_rate":60},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1325193907,"creation_date":1325193907,"body":"<p>I don't think you should need to vary the concentration of the GelRed.  Mine came with instructions for the exact concentration and how to dilute.  Optionally salt can be added, which I did, and it has worked for me.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have only done this with Post-staining.  1-2.5% agarose with TAE.  Used a 10,000x solution from Phenix research. The gelred stock and working solution needs to kept in the dark.  I am assuming you have a transilluminator and (optional) filters to visual though. GelRed has similar excitation and emission [wavelength] properties as EtBr, so a standard transilluminator and filter should work without any changes.  It will not be visible with the naked eye.<\/p>\n\n<p>That being said there are a ton of things that can go wrong in casting the gel, eletrophoresis, staining, and visualization.  If bands are visible but just blurry I was suspect there is more of a problem with either the gel creation or eletrophoresis though. Make sure agarose is completely clear and cooled down a little before pouring. Otherwise voltage is one of the main things I have noticed that can have significant affects on how sharp or blurry bands appear.  You might try different % gels and different voltages.  There are formulas that can help you estimate the best value for each of those.<\/p>\n","answer_id":389,"question_id":101,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/101/what-conditions-should-i-use-for-gel-red-staining","last_activity_date":1428622109,"creation_date":1323964095,"answer_count":2,"title":"What conditions should I use for Gel Red staining?","body":"<p>What are the optimal staining conditions when using Gel Red? So far, since we have started using it, the gels ran in our lab have been of very poor qua