differentiation, the cells of the developing organism undergo huge changes, which result in cells, functioning \"completely\" differently. Two cells are considered to be of different types if they are having different sets of template-competent genes, though most of the genes in the human genome are common even in highly differentiated cells. Being able to produce specific proteins from the same genome is achieved by something called open chromatin state of the DNA. What I would like to ask is why can't this specific conformation of the DNA be reversed as this would likely answer the title of this question? I would also like to have some tips on further reading in the topic of DNA conformations and about DNA generally.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><em>I used Gabor Forgacs's and Stuart A. Newman's book called Biological Physics of the Developing Embryo<\/em> <\/p>\n","question_id":31200,"tags":["dna","development"],"score":6,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":74,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b7a5fd36fabd85460917e4caa11b994b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15274,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15274/lfrc","reputation":116,"display_name":"LFRC"},"closed_date":1428651216,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/41CJK.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5762,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5762/the-last-word","reputation":4553,"display_name":"The Last Word","accept_rate":100},"score":2,"post_id":31190,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428570795,"comment_id":52147,"body":"could you please elaborate on how you went about solving it"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":3,"post_id":31190,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428624092,"comment_id":52184,"body":"I&#39;m voting to close this question as off-topic because it is better suited for physics.SE."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31190/blood-as-newtonian-flow-and-poiseuille-law","last_activity_date":1428612639,"creation_date":1428568958,"answer_count":0,"title":"Blood as newtonian flow and Poiseuille law","body":"<p>For a prep exam: <\/p>\n\n<p>A healtly pacient has a carotid with the following characteristics:<\/p>\n\n<p>intern ratio: 𝑅= 2.8 mm, \n𝑃2 = 89 𝑚𝑚𝐻𝑔, \n𝑃1 = 90 𝑚𝑚𝐻𝑔,\n 𝜇blood = 3.5 cp,\n𝐿=10.0 cm.<\/p>\n\n<p>Using the following equations calculate:<\/p>\n\n<p>$$V(r)=\\frac{P_1 - P_2}{4 \\mu L}R^2 [1-(\\frac{r}{R})^2]$$\n$$V_{max}= V(r=0)$$\n$$\\overline{V} = \\frac{Q}{A}=\\frac{1}{2}V_{max}$$\n$$Q=\\frac{\\pi(P_1 - P_2)}{8 \\mu L}R^4$$<\/p>\n\n<p>where P_1 and P_2 are the mean pressure to in and out the vase, R is ve vase radius, L is the length of the vase segment and $\\mu$ is the viscosity of the fluid.<\/p>\n\n<p>A healthy patient has a carotid withe the following characteristics: intern radius R = 2.8 mm, $P_2$ = 89 mmHg, $P_1$ = 90 mmHg, $\\mu_{blood}$=3.5cp, L = 10cm.<\/p>\n\n<p>Using the previous equations calculate:<\/p>\n\n<p>a) Mean velocity on the carotid artery Rta: 0.372 m/s\nb) Maximum velocity Rta: 0.744 m/s\nc) caudal on the carotid artery Rta: $9.16x10^{-6} m^{-6}$<\/p>\n\n<p>I have tried to solve this problem but when i try to replace changing the units to the adecuate I have not the correct answer<\/p>\n","question_id":31190,"tags":["physiology","homework"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":false,"view_count":30,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1428612639},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/87b47bc5cd0083b3bd81d2c8a8ae02b2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15265,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15265/zero-hsy","reputation":11,"display_name":"zero_hsy"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":2,"post_id":31189,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428568123,"comment_id":52146,"body":"A low IC50 marks a sensitive cell line, a high a resistant."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uTYSx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14826,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14826/cagliari2005","reputation":2361,"display_name":"cagliari2005"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428611897,"creation_date":1428611587,"body":"<p>From this <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/30355/what-is-the-ic50-exactly/30357#30357\">post<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IC50\" rel=\"nofollow\">IC50<\/a> is the concentration of inhibitor required to reduce the activity of a molecule/protein by one-half. It is the inverse of <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EC50\" rel=\"nofollow\">EC50<\/a>. Usually inhibition curves looks sigmoidal so the IC50 is the middle point of the S curve. Here an example. (Note that the Y-axis can be pretty much anything, like enzyme activity and the X-axis is the concentration in a logarithmic scale).<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/68HEc.gif\" alt=\"Illustration\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Now for your actual question. The IC50 you got is by plotting a measure of the cell death rate vs the concentration of the drug. IC50 is expressed as a concentration so the higher the concentration of drug needed to kill the cell line the more resistant that cell line is. If the IC50 is very low then the concentration (or amount) of drug needed to kill the cell line is also very low which means the cell line is more sensitive.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31206,"question_id":31189,"up_vote_count