reased likelihood of it developing in the children but it is by no means a guarantee (even for dominant mendelian traits if mutation occurs). Few things are entirely genetically determined."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/dITzT.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14698,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14698/sleepses","reputation":532,"display_name":"Sleepses"},"score":0,"post_id":31194,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428586581,"comment_id":52164,"body":"In the case of schizophrenia, it has always been evident that there is a genetic factor. However it has not been identified. More recent hypotheses suggest <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epigenetics\" rel=\"nofollow\">epigenetic<\/a> mechanisms. Meaning the trait can be inherited, but is very sensitive to short-term environmental changes."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1sIMq.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"post_id":31194,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428589486,"comment_id":52166,"body":"Welcome to Biology.SE. Your question reveals that you probably don&#39;t know the concepts of Mendelian segregation/dominance/additivity/pleiotropy and epistasis. You should check out those terms on wikipedia. Also You will probably want to increase your understanding of heritability. <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/16858/are-people-genetically-predisposed-to-being-interested-in-specific-fields-ideas/16862#16862\">Here<\/a> is an answer that link to 4 other posts that talk about heritability."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31194/do-the-traces-genetic-diseases-remain-in-families","last_activity_date":1428577555,"creation_date":1428574290,"answer_count":0,"title":"Do The Traces Genetic Diseases Remain in families?","body":"<p>I know that there are certain di