ch as potassium chloride. In certain situations, a cold compress is recommended.\"<\/p>\n","answer_id":10467,"question_id":10466,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c7ae3b82b2d54e2f09895e5f1fc0d0fa?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":15271,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15271/ashley-wagner","reputation":11,"display_name":"Ashley Wagner"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428559925,"creation_date":1428559925,"body":"<p>The most common IV drip that would be sent home with a pet owner is Ringer's solution. This fluid is also commonly injected as a subcutaneous (between muscle and skin) bolus into both cats and dogs. Although IV administration is more efficient, this fluid is completely harmless if an IV catheter were dislodged allowing it to accumulate in the surrounding tissue. <\/p>\n","answer_id":31188,"question_id":10466,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/10466/what-happens-if-an-iv-drip-with-a-saline-solution-slips-out-of-the-vein-but-kee","last_activity_date":1428559925,"creation_date":1379368075,"answer_count":2,"title":"What happens if an IV drip with a saline solution slips out of the vein, but keeps dripping into the body?","body":"<p>A patient has a saline solution IV drip into the vein. They have somehow moved around and the needle has fallen out of the vein, but remained in the body. Nobody has noticed and for a few hours water has accumulated like a balloon in the arm.<\/p>\n\n<p>What happens? Is it dangerous? If untreated, would the body absorb the water, or would it remain as a balloon / pocket? If a pocket of water forms, what is the treatment?<\/p>\n","question_id":10466,"tags":["hematology","hydration"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":10467,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":4562,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-V2vCnbGHEEA/AAAAAAAAAAI