8&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":0,"post_id":31059,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428516198,"comment_id":52129,"body":"I would also ask - especially given the context of the question - whether there&#39;s any sort of training effect.  Certainly I can perceive a difference between classical music compressed with MP3, and the same piece at full CD resolution.  Which itself involves some downsampling compression: I recall that when CDs first came out, some audiophiles claimed to hear a quality difference between them and an analog recording, though I never could."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"score":1,"post_id":31171,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428511445,"comment_id":52121,"body":"I guess you had to dig really deep to find this paper.... thank you!"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428538764,"creation_date":1428505398,"body":"<p>The <strong>frequency limen<\/strong>, or <strong>frequency resolution<\/strong> can be determined in various ways using <em>psychophysical measures<\/em>. You refer to a simultaneous method, in which two (or more) frequencies are presented at the same time. This has consequences for the test as different frequencies are perceived with different perceived loudness under constant sound pressure levels, meaning that additional cues are present besides pitch cues. <\/p>\n\n<p>One carefully controlled study <a href=\"http://www.ee.columbia.edu/~dpwe/e6820/papers/ZwicFS57-crband.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Zwicker et al (1957)<\/a> in this regard defined the <strong>critical band<\/strong> basically as \"<em>those frequencies where no intensity summation occurs<\/em>\", meaning that adding those frequencies (below or above the center frequency) do not result in differences in loudness perception (as expressed in <em>acoustic threshold<\/em> of the center frequency). This method nicely prevents loudness summation cues by deploying them in the criterion. This article shows the following picture (after <a href=\"http://www.ee.columbia.edu/~dpwe/e6820/papers/ZwicFS57-crband.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Zwicker et al. (1957)<\/a>):<\/p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/IVYT8.png\" alt=\"Difference limen\"><\/p>\n\n<p>The <strong>critical band<\/strong> (upper graph) is dependent on frequency, and ranges from 0.1 kHz to >2 kHz. <\/p>\n\n<p>The markedly lower difference limen of 3.6 Hz as touched upon in the comments may have been obtained using an alternative psychophysical test where the test frequency is <strong>modulated<\/strong> by another frequency (bottom graph). This procedure is based on adding a frequency to a certain sinusoidal stimulus, basically resulting in a single stimulus instead of two (or more). This procedure is technically not defined as a critical band and indeed results in a difference limen of ~3.5 hz and up. The other graph plotted in the figure is a <strong>masking procedure<\/strong> (middle plot), which basically determines the physiological overlap between frequencies in the cochlea in the intensity domain by determining the amount of masking from one frequency by another. <\/p>\n\n<p>NB: The authors worked with headphones so no effects of direction. <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference<\/strong><br>\n<a href=\"http://www.ee.columbia.edu/~dpwe/e6820/papers/ZwicFS57-crband.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Zwicker et al. <em>JASA<\/em> 1957; <strong>29<\/strong>: 548-57<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":31171,"question_id":31059,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1428538764}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31059/whats-the-frequency-resolution-of-the-human-ear","last_activity_date":1428538764,"creation_date":1428150915,"answer_count":1,"title":"What's the frequency resolution of the human ear?","body":"<p>I was thinking about audio compression (namely mp3), that \"filters\" out sound that we would not likely hear.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The MP3 lossy audio data compression algorithm takes advantage of a perceptual limitation of human hearing called auditory masking.\n  from: <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MP3\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MP3<\/a><\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I've also checked the wiki entry for <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Auditory_masking\" rel=\"nofollow\">auditory masking<\/a>, and found this: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>If two sounds of two different frequencies are played at the same time, two separate sounds can often be heard rather than a combination tone. The ability to hear frequencies separately is known as frequency resolution or frequency selectivity. When signals are perceived as a combination tone, they are said to reside in the same critical bandwidth.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>My question is how much is this critical bandwidth or what's the smallest frequency difference we can perceive as two different tones, if you wish. Let's assume that both tones are equally loud, are coming from the same direction and distance and we are in a quiet room - so basically we eliminate as much noise and affecting phenomenons as possible.<\/p>\n\n<p>As @ sanchises pointed out (thank you again!) in the comment section the frequency resolution is 3.6Hz between 1 and 2kHz. But since perception threshold is a function of the pitch of the sound I'd assume that the ability to resolve two tones would change with pitch too. Does anybody have any data on that? For example resolution X pitch graph.<\/p>\n","question_id":31059,"tags":["sensation","perception","hearing"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":31171,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":327,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1428505566},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2aee3158c6eb5d085dfc62cba64d7036?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":608,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/608/roflcoptrexception","reputation":255,"display_name":"RoflcoptrException","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":1375,"edited":false,"creation_date":1331477464,"comment_id":1683,"body":"When you say &quot;yellow&quot; do you mean bright yellow or brownish/cream?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2aee3158c6eb5d085dfc62cba64d7036?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":608,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/608/roflcoptrexception","reputation":255,"display_name":"RoflcoptrException","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":1375,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1331479233,"comment_id":1685,"body":"It&#39;s rather bright yellow."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f9fca3702076c969eb513703a020c7db?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":510,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/510/preece","reputation":1144,"display_name":"Preece"},"score":0,"post_id":1