ns. Its good for allele diagnosis etc."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/nOk2h.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15136/wolgast","reputation":522,"display_name":"Wolgast","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":31099,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"edited":false,"creation_date":1428315555,"comment_id":51959,"body":"The restriction sites are the sequence properties. Some people will have a different amount of them. Otherwise there wouldn&#39;t be patterns (the RFLPs) to compare.  Hence you can use the RFLPs/restriction sites as genetic markers."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Ic4na.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14735,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14735/nandor-poka","reputation":2578,"display_name":"Nandor Poka","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":31099,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428319787,"comment_id":51960,"body":"Yes restrictions sites are sequence properties but they are 6-8 bases long, so there are waaay too many of them. You keep using RFLP the wrong way, that is the name of the technique / phenomenon noting more. It`s not like VNTR or SNP. You can identify SNPs with RFLP."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fcf9d3bdac2c3fa35177730c31b34f79?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":6307,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6307/canadianer","reputation":6147,"display_name":"canadianer"},"score":1,"post_id":31099,"edited":false,"creation_date":1428340564,"comment_id":51972,"body":"I have rolled back the edit to the original version. There are many cases in literature of RFLPs being referred to as markers, which they are."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/uTYSx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14826,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14826/cagliari2005","reputation":2361,"display_name":"cagliari2005"},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1428340670,"creation_date":1428337681,"body":"<p>SNPs are much denser than RFLPs and VNTRs therefore the DNA resolution is much greater with SNPs. VNTRs were historically used for <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_linkage\" rel=\"nofollow\">linkage mapping<\/a> while SNPs allowed for association studies (e.g. <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genome-wide_association_study\" rel=\"nofollow\">GWA studies<\/a>). Therefore your question goes down to what are the differences between linkage mapping and association studies.<\/p>\n\n<p>They are both forward genetic methods which aim to identify a genetic modification provoking a trait.<\/p>\n\n<p>The two major differences between both approaches are 1) linkage mapping requires a pedigree but can be performed using a fairly small sample size while 2) association studies can be performed at the population level but usually require a much larger sample size.<\/p>\n\n<p>Both approaches require markers but for different reasons. For linkage mapping, markers, such as microsatellites, are used to delimit the genomic region associated with the trait and take advantage of recombination events in the genome to pin down that region. This, of course, requires both 1) recombinant individuals in the pedigree and 2) at least one marker that is co-inherited with the trait. Linkage mapping allows to find virtually any genetic modifications, such as a genomic deletion, but only in the case of a genetic modification showing high penetrance.<\/p>\n\n<p>For association studies, markers are the actual genomic modification themselves (usually SNPs) and are used directly in statistical tests (often a logistic or linear regression) for association with the trait. This means that either 1) the causal marker is available or 2) at least one marker is highly co-inherited with the causal mutation (i.e. in linkage disequilibrium). Association studies allows to find both low- or high-penetrance mutations, given a sufficiently big sample size. Also an association study can be conducted in the presence of a non-discrete (i.e. linear) phenotype which one cannot use in linkage mapping.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another difference is that linkage mapping does not require any a priori knowledge of the genomic modification causing the trait while association studies do (as markers are statistically associated with the phenotype).<\/p>\n\n<p>Usually both methods will highlight, with varying resolution based on the phenotype and markers used, the genomic region causing a trait but rarely the actual causal mutation will be found with 100% certainty.<\/p>\n","answer_id":31104,"question_id":31099,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1428340670}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31099/markers-for-human-genetic-mapping","last_activity_date":1428340670,"creation_date":1428311846,"answer_count":1,"title":"Markers for human genetic mapping","body":"<p>For human genetic mapping several different types of markers are used:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>RFLPs (Restriction Fragment Length Polymorphisms)<\/li>\n<li>VNTRs (Variable Number of Tandem Repeats) such as mini- and microsatellites<\/li>\n<li>SNPs (Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>What are the pro's and con's of using each type?<\/p>\n\n<p>Do any of these markers have a specific functionality in human genetic mapping, or can they all be used for the same purposes?<\/p>\n","question_id":31099,"tags":["genetics","molecular-genetics","human-genetics","human-genome"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":31104,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":67,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1428340110},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/ZwVSN.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6576,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6576/paze","reputation":676,"display_name":"Paze","accept_rate":82},"closed_date":1435000183,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":0,"post_id":31101,"edited":false,"creation_date":1431761237,"comment_id":54810,"body":"Can you be a bit more specific? Are you asking about the role of cholesterol in cells in general, or its function in lipoproteins, specifially in VLDL, or ... ?"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/31101/cholesterols-role-in-lipid-uptake","last_activity_date":1428322032,"creation_date":1428322032,"answer_count":0,"title":"Cholesterol's role in lipid uptake","body":"<p>I'm studying the digestion of fats and I understand that our dietary fats mostly consist of triglycerides. We absorb the fats and eventually they end up in a muscle/adipose cell for storage (as triglycerides) or for oxidation for energy.<\/p>\n\n<p>However I don't understand exactly where cholesterol plays in? I read about lipids being synthesized by the liver being exported by VLDL and then taken up by cells. We're moving closer to cholesterol here but I still don't see the connection.<\/p>\n","question_id":31101,"tags":["human-biology","biochemistry","metabolism","fat-metabolism"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":false,"view_count":42,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/96feab2e74adc3739519b6db71d14c38?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13344,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13344/drowsy","reputation":31,"display_name":"Drowsy"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar